  "prompt": "Besides platinum+rhodium for NOx reduction and platinum+palladium for CO reduction, which catalyst can be used in catalytic converters?",
  "response": "In addition to platinum (Pt) and rhodium (Rh) for NO\u2093 reduction and platinum (Pt) with palladium (Pd) for carbon monoxide (CO) reduction, catalytic converters can incorporate several other catalysts to enhance performance and reduce emissions. Some notable alternatives and supplementary catalysts include:\n\n1. **Cerium Oxide (CeO\u2082):**\n   - **Function:** Acts as an oxygen storage component, helping to maintain the optimal oxygen level for effective oxidation and reduction reactions.\n   - **Benefits:** Enhances the efficiency of the primary catalysts (Pt, Pd, Rh) by providing a steady supply of oxygen, which is crucial for the conversion of CO and hydrocarbons (HC) into less harmful substances like CO\u2082 and water.\n\n2. **Base Metal Catalysts:**\n   - **Examples:** Copper (Cu), Manganese (Mn), and Nickel (Ni).\n   - **Function:** Serve as alternative catalytic materials that can facilitate oxidation and reduction reactions.\n   - **Benefits:** These metals are generally less expensive than platinum group metals (PGMs) and can be used to reduce overall catalyst costs. However, they may offer lower catalytic activity and durability compared to PGMs.\n\n3. **Transition Metal Catalysts on Zeolite Supports:**\n   - **Examples:** Iron (Fe), Cobalt (Co), and Vanadium (V) supported on zeolites.\n   - **Function:** Provide active sites for the catalytic conversion of pollutants.\n   - **Benefits:** Zeolite supports offer high surface areas and stability, enhancing the dispersion and effectiveness of the transition metals.\n\n4. **Non-PGM Catalysts:**\n   - **Emerging Technologies:** Research is ongoing into catalysts that do not rely on PGMs, such as perovskite oxides and other advanced materials.\n   - **Function:** Aim to provide efficient catalytic activity for emission control without the high costs associated with PGMs.\n   - **Benefits:** Potential for lower costs and reduced reliance on scarce materials, though many are still in the developmental or early implementation stages.\n\n5. **Three-Way Catalysts (TWCs) Enhancements:**\n   - **Composition:** Often combine multiple PGMs with other materials like cerium oxide to optimize the simultaneous reduction of NO\u2093 and oxidation of CO and hydrocarbons.\n   - **Function:** Enable effective control of multiple pollutants in automotive exhaust.\n   - **Benefits:** Improved versatility and efficiency in meeting stringent emission standards.\n\n**Summary:**\nWhile platinum, rhodium, and palladium remain the cornerstone metals for catalytic converters due to their high catalytic activity, incorporating additives like cerium oxide and exploring base and transition metal catalysts can enhance performance, reduce costs, and improve the longevity of catalytic converters. Advances in catalyst formulations continue to evolve, aiming for more efficient and sustainable emission control technologies.",
